[32m+[m[32m                                 NOTES FOR CLARIFICATION AND EXPLANATION OF[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 CERTAIN MATTERS IN THE ENGLISH TRANSLATION[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                           OF SRIYUKTESHVAR GIRI MAHARAJ'S[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 COMMENTARIES ON THE SRIMAD BHAGAVAD GITA[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHome                             The reader is asked to kindly read this section so that there may be a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 clearer understanding of some of the peculiarities of this translation.[m
[32m+[m[32mCover Page[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 It can be generally stated that all material in parentheses - "( )" -[m
[32m+[m[32mPreface to the                   including the parentheses themselves, are from the original text, unless[m
[32m+[m[32mpresent English                  specifically noted to be otherwise; whereas all material in brackets -[m
[32m+[m[32mEdition                          "[ ]" - are of the translator's for the purpose of clarifying context,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 connotations and definitions of words. All footnotes and the text of[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami                            footnotes are translated directly from the original text. There are no[m
[32m+[m[32mSatyananda's                     annotations by the translator in regards to these footnotes from the[m
[32m+[m[32mPreface to the                   original. The notes by the translator have been clearly stated with the[m
[32m+[m[32mBengali Edition                  term, "Translator's note:", and these notes are only for clarification and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 do not attempt to explain the work of the author.[m
[32m+[m[32mIntroduction[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Clarification of certain words:[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 1[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 2                        The word "Consciousness," with an upper case "C", is used to[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 3                        translate the word "Chaitanya," which refers to Supreme[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 4                        Consciousness or Supreme Beingness. The word "consciousness" with[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 5                        a lower case "c" is used to define "chitta," or consciousness in the[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 6                        human being as part of the entire mental construct. Where[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 7                        "chitta" [consciousness] and "mana" [mind] have been used to mean[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 8                        the same thing and when either word has been in close physical[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 9                        proximity in the written text with the word[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Chaitanya" [Consciousness], the word "mind" has been used in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 translation in order to not cause confusion. For example:[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "consciousness becomes absorbed in Consciousness." That type of[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/note.html (1 of 5)4/18/2006 2:41:55 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 10                  passage would be translated as "mind becomes absorbed in[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 11                  Consciousness." In general, the word "mind," as used in this[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 12                  translation, is in reference to the entire mental faculty, including[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 13                  human consciousness. When either term - mana or chitta - has been[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 14                  spoken of as a specific part of the whole mental faculty,! it has been[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 15                  translated as such (showing the specificity).[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 16[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 17                  This use of upper and lower case is intentional throughout the[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 18                  translation and includes other words such as "self" and "Self," etc.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The word "karma" as used in the Gita, and in Hindu society, has[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 always meant "work," "act," "action," or some complex variations of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 such. Unlike the popular understanding of the word "karma" prevalent[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 today, the word as used in the Gita DOES NOT mean some kind of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 principle of retribution and reward according to merit. The issue of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fruits of actions ["karmaphala"] is different and separate from the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 meaning of the word "karma." The most obvious example is in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 term "karma yoga" or "karmayoga." This refers to yoga [union][m
[32m+[m[32m                                 through some act or action. It has nothing to do with any reciprocating[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 law or judgment. It would be more accurate to use the word[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "prarabdha" if one wants to refer to fruits of actions carried over from[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the past. It is essential to NOT think of the word "karma" as a principle[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of retribution and reward in order to understand many passages in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Gita. In many sections of this translation, the various definitions of the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 word "karma" have been provided! in brackets, such as: "karma[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [work]...," or "karma [action]...."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The word "samsara" in this translation basically refers to "life in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 world," or "worldly existence." Again, unlike some interpretations of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the word in the present day which give it a negative connotation, in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Bengali, this is not so. It simply means "worldly existence and the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 matters associated with it." It is neither good nor bad.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Sometimes, certain terms such as "vashikar avastha" [separate words][m
[32m+[m[32m                                 appear also as "vashikaravastha," [compound word] and both are used[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 in the same chapter. The two versions have the same meaning. In[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Sanskritic languages two words can become compounded into one[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 word for various literary reasons. However, those reasons cannot be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 transmitted via a translation. But for the sake of accuracy and in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 keeping with the letter of the original text, words with these seeming[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 discrepancies in their appearances have been transliterated as they[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 appear in the original, in whichever form that may be.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/note.html (2 of 5)4/18/2006 2:41:55 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Brahman, Brahma, brahmin" - The spellings of "Brahman" and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Atman" - terms referring to the Absolute Being are from standard[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 transliterations of those words by luminaries of the past. In some[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 translations and transliterations of the present day, the spelling for[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Brahman" is written as "Brahma," or "Brahm." This translation has[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 chosen to not go in that direction for several reasons:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 This translation does not use phonetic symbols, which would be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 necessary to differentiate between "Brahma" - the Absolute - which[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 uses a very short "a" at the end of the word [pronounced like "Brahm[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 (a)"], and "Brahma" - the creator aspect of the Supreme - which uses a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 long "a" at the end of the word [pronounced like, "Brahmaa"]. The[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 spelling "Brahm" has not been used because that form of the word does[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 not exist in Bengali or Sanskrit [with no continuation of the "m" at all],[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 although it is used in modern Hindi. In Sanskrit and Bengali, the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 pronunciation is always with a short "a" at the end, slightly continuing[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the "m." This translation has tried to stay closer to the Sanskrit and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Bengali in its transliterations as that is the source for this work. This[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 translator has found it easiest to use the terms "Brahman" [where the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "n" is only a nasality and not a letter] for the Absolute, and "Brahma"[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 for the creator aspect.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The word "brahmin" with a lower case "b" and the letter "i" in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 word refers to the scholarly or priestly caste of Hindu society. In[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Bengali, it is really pronounced as "braahmon." [In spiritual[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 philosophy the caste system is not physical, as has been explained in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the commentaries of the holy and revered author.][m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 For these reasons, standard spellings as used by past luminaries have[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 been the simplest to use, especially because this translation does not[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 use phonetic symbols.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Transliteration of Sanskrit slokas: The transliteration of the Sanskrit[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 slokas have been left in their simplest forms because this translation[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 does not use phonetic symbols.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 With few exceptions, where it would otherwise be impossible to make[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sentence sense, the translation tries to reflect the length, the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 terminology used within, and the cadence of the old-style, literary[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Bengali sentences of the revered author. (However, the basis for[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 punctuation in the translation is from modern English.) What may[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 seem unusual in terms of the structure and cadence is there to reflect[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/note.html (3 of 5)4/18/2006 2:41:55 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the original Bengali. The translation maintains that to do otherwise[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 would be to take liberties on the original intention as expressed in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 rhythm and shape of the writing of the revered author, and thus meddle[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 into interpretation, which is contrary to the purposes of this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 translation. The interpretations are left to the readers and practitioners.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 It is well worth stating that the Bengali in the Gita - both Swami[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Satyanandaji's and Swami Sriyukteshvar Giriji Maharaj's - is of a very[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 old and formal style. No one speaks Bengali in that way; no one even[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 writes in Bengali in that way any more. That was the style from the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 late nineteenth century and used up until the middle of the twentieth[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 century. The translator had to stay true to what was being written, as[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 well as HOW the phrasing was. Otherwise, it would have been easy to[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fall into interpreting the work, instead of simply translating it.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Here is a simple example [this is more exemplary of the body of the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Gita]. There is a difference between saying, "That Consciousness is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Brahman," and "That Consciousness - That is the One Who is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Brahman." The second statement, if read correctly, is more emphatic,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 telling the reader to understand that that Consciousness is Itself[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Brahman and nothing else. In Bengali, one can make that change with[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 one letter!!! The translator has tried to stay true to those types of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 things, even though they do not necessarily read like proper English.[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Other translations might simply say it in the first way, because it is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 written in more "correct" English, and it's easy to put aside the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 emphasis made by that one Bengali letter.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The dashes and double dashes, the redundant usage of words - such as[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 in the phrase: "The one who focuses in Atman -- he is...." instead of the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 more "correct": "One who focuses in Atman is...etc. etc." (without the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 second "he"), and all such things are completely intentional. The[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 translator is aware of how it might look, but there is no other way to[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 get the emphasis on to the English language and be true to the Bengali[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 at the same time. The translator is aware that the sentences might seem[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 awkward.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 As far as meanings being cryptic, the translator has left what seems to[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 be mysterious just as it was written.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 This explanation of the English translation to Sriyukteshvar Giri[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Maharaj's commentaries on the Srimad Bhagavad Gita may be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 updated to include other issues of clarification that the readers[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 may have.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/note.html (4 of 5)4/18/2006 2:41:55 PM[m
