[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 perform Kriya; I have no power of discrimination. So, O Kutasthachaitanya,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 I take refuge in You. Please teach me what is dutiful and what is not [7 - 9].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 When this condition of openness occurs, Kutasthachaitanya is pleased and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 through inner perception, this type of unmanufactured truths are experienced[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [10]. Just as the physical body naturally goes through the manifestations of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 childhood, youth and old age, in the same way, the subtle body also naturally[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 takes up another body after death. But Consciousness is never destroyed,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and that which is without a beginning is never born also. The wise ones are[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 never deluded by all these matters of birth and death. Therefore, it is not[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 right to just listen to clever sayings and become engaged in that. Kriya[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 should be taken up [11 - 13]. The one who is not distressed by the fleeting[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 objects of pleasure and pain is the one who is qualified for the path of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 liberation. Therefore, learning to endure these things is imperative [14 - 15].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 This body and its faculties exist in appearance only; they remain only for a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 while and are impermanent. The All-Pervading Consciousness is Eternal[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Substance; it is not destroyed by anything. Therefore, one should destroy[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 even this impermanent name along with the appearance of faculties and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 perform the Consciousness-revealing Kriya [16 - 18]. "This Causeless,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Infinite, Eternal and ever-existing-as-Itself Atman is never destroyed with[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the body. Only in ignorance is It perceived to be the slayer or the slain."[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Understanding this statement, no one endeavors to meaningless killing [19 -[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 21]. This Eternal, All-pervading, Universal Atman-substance cannot be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 corrupted by air, fire, water or weapons. As if casting off worn-out clothing,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 He discards a body that no longer works and thereafter takes a new body.[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Upon experiencing this Consciousness-substance, which is beyond the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 organs of perception, the organs of action and inner organs [mind], one[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 should not grieve over the loss of these insignificant mental propensities etc.[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [22 - 25] If one is deluded and ascertains that the Atman has birth and death,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 even then it is certain that if birth happens then there must be death, and if[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 death happens then there must be birth. It is not appropriate to lament over[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 this unavoidable matter [26 -27]. This Eternal Consciousness cannot be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 killed. From the unmanifest Nature of this Consciousness was this elemental[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 world created, remaining in which - in the manifested state for a while - It[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 merges back into Itself at the time of dissolution. Therefore, why be sad[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 over this? When prajna is established by the Sadguru-graced Kriya, one is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 awed by experiencing all this; one is also at wonderment while speaking[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 about this and listening to this, but unless the consciousness is stilled, it is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 not understandable, even upon hearing this over and over [28 - 30]. There is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 no other way for the embodied to be liberated besides this effortless Atman-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 dharma, by which one acquires the highest - the Bliss of Brahman [31 -32].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Turning away from this revelation of Consciousness causes doubt even in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 existence of oneself and one falls into great delusion. Then one becomes[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 enslaved to the elemental world‚Äôs and the ego‚Äôs faculties and must go[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 through great suffering [33 - 36]. But one acquires the Brahmanda with[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 successful practice. If one dies while practicing, then one dies without[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 suffering and goes to the most excellent place as prescribed by the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 samskaras. Therefore, gain and loss are the same. Having such knowledge,[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter2.html (34 of 36)4/18/2006 2:42:00 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 one should endure impermanent pleasure and pain and be immersed in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 performing the Consciousness-revealing Kriya [37 - 38]. This is the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 jnanayoga of the wise ones. It is imperative to do this yogakriya for the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 realization of this Knowledge. The practice of this does not require all kinds[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of mental processes; self-discipline is enough. Therefore, there is no[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 possibility of any obstacles as well. It is never unsuccessful. Just a little[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 performance of it destroys the suffering of the mind and brings contentment[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [39 - 41]. The Vedas and such treatises are filled with tempting methods to[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fulfill all kinds of desires based on sattva, raja and tama gunas. Therefore,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 one should renounce the cravings for enjoyment, endure pleasure and pain,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 go beyond the three gunas, and reside in Tranquility, because those who are[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 content in the Bliss of Brahman have no lack of happiness [42 - 46].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Therefore, yogakriya is the highest karma, not the trivial, result-hankering[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Vedic acts. One should in no case disregard the practice of this [yogakriya].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 No one has control over the result of any action; thus one should not be[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 anxious over that. Therefore, one should know success and failure as the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 same and be immersed in Kriya [47 - 49]. By knowing the method of this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 yogakriya, sages extinguish the perception of both good and wrong acts,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 liberate themselves from the bindings of this worldly life and attain[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Kaivalyapada [50 - 51]. The mind is captivated by many religious and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 secular matters. When one goes beyond this fort of delusion, a non-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 attachment about all things manifests and a tranquil prajna is realized [52 -[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 53]. Upon having this experience, a certain enquiry arises in the rajoguna[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 that: who are called sthitaprajna; how do they teach; how do they reside; and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 how do they move? [54] Then it is experienced in the Kutasthachaitanya[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 that -- withdrawing the senses as a tortoise pulls in its limbs, being without[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fear and anger, discerning happiness and unhappinesss as the same, being[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 without desires of the mind and without affection or dislike for anything, and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 remaining content within oneself - are the signs of sthitaprajna [55 -58]. It is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 true that by fasting the senses become listless and turn away from sense[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 pleasures, but the cravings do not end. This is proved when the senses return[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 to their healthy states and again capture the minds of even the most careful[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and highly knowledgeable ones. Therefore, one should completely control[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the juggernaut of senses and reside in the Self. This is the teaching of the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 ones with sthitaprajna [59 - 61]. Thinking about sense objects causes a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 liking for them which leads to obsession with having them. At the lack of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 such things, anger arises which gives birth to delusion. Delusion destroys[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 memory and it prevents self-knowledge which makes one as if dead. There[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 is no possibility of tranquility without the revelation of Knowledge by[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 yogakriya, and without tranquility happiness is difficult to attain. When the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 senses are restless from thinking about sense objects, the mind follows them,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and is like a boat at the mercy of winds on the sea, and thus wisdom is lost.[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 For this reason the ones with sthitaprajna detach themselves from the objects[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of sight, sound, touch etc., fulfill the partaking of sense objects without[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 affection or hatred, eradicate pleasure and sorrow, and by doing so, live in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 divine cheerfulness with the mind at peace [62 - 68]. Not turning their[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 attention to the things of sight, sound, touch etc. that stir the senses,[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter2.html (35 of 36)4/18/2006 2:42:00 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 completely filled with the Bliss of Brahman as the sea is filled with water,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 residing in an awakened state in the Kutastha which is inaccessible by the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 knowledge from the elemental world, renouncing attachment, desire and ego,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fulfilling all of the resultant predestiny caused by the past like the rivers and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 streams gathering all their water and flowing into the sea, the ones with[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sthitaprajna are liberated from the entrapment of samsara. Thus, they "move[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 into"* Kaivalyapada. Because of unending desires, those who are desirous[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 take birth again and again and remain bound to this worldly life [69 - 71].[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 This [the state of the ones with sthitaprajna] is called residing in Atman-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Consciousness, which is the death of all delusion. If the jiva can be in this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 state at the time of death, it merges into the Supreme Vishnu and attains[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Kaivalyapada [72].[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [*The quotation marks and the translated text within are in the original,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 defining how the ones with sthitaprajna move.][m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Thus ends the second chapter of the yogashastra upanishad Srimad Bhagavad[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Gita with analysis via various scriptures of this country and the West, along[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 with spiritual commentary.[m
