[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter5.html (10 of 16)4/18/2006 2:42:05 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Those who have stilled their minds in the aforementioned way, and who, by[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 experiencing Consciousness as the same and immutable in all things in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Universe, have attained the Brahman-condition -- they are liberated from the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 many types of delusionary kleshas such as affinity, hatred, etc. These types[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of jivanmukta saddhakas are not elated at gaining any pleasurable things, nor[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 are they despondent over getting something that is unwanted. -20-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 bahyasparsheshvasaktatma vindatyatmani yat sukham[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sa brahmayogayuktatma sukhamakshyayamashnuhte -21-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Poetically:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Unattached from physical things[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Tasting supreme happiness within[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Mind solely in Brahman[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Enjoying eternally the indestructible supreme happiness -21-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Commentary:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Those who, by not having become corrupted by attachment to physical[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 things, have kept in the state of the Consciousness-Self -- they experience[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 that Tranquility-filled Soul-happiness and finally merge into the Supreme[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Brahman, and thereby attain that indestructible Peace and Supreme[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Happiness of Kaivalya. -21-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 ye hi samsprashaja bhoga duhknayonaya eva te[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 adyantavantah kounteya na teshu ramate budhah -22-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Poetically:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The enjoyment of things is the cause of pleasure and sorrow[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Affinity, hatred, jealousy, intoxicants are one and the same[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 It happens, it goes, there is no permanence[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Therefore, the wise do not indulge in these -22-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Commentary:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 All of the bhoga-oriented pleasures that arise from the union with sensory[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 things are the source of all of the types of suffering. They manifest as[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sorrow; even at the time of enjoyment there is sorrow and misery; even the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 samskaras [tendencies] because of these are filled with suffering. And[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 because the minutely manifesting sattva, rajas and tamas guna-connected[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 characteristics are fighting with each other, these pleasures remain only for a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 minute amount of time. It is for this reason that the discriminating wise ones[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 never are attracted to these. It is expressed in this way in the Patanjal[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 philosophical treatise: as in -[m
[32m+[m
