[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter7.html (16 of 16)4/18/2006 2:42:07 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj  www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 CHAPTER EIGHT[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 TARAKABRAHMAYOGA[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHome                             Arjuna said:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mCover Page                       kim tadbrahma kimadhyatmam kim karma purushottama[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 adhibhutancha kim proktamadhidaivam kimuchyate -1-[m
[32m+[m[32mPreface to the                   adhiyajnah katham kohtra dehehsmin madhusudana[m
[32m+[m[32mpresent English                  prayanakale cha katham jneyohsi niyatatmabhih -2-[m
[32m+[m[32mEdition[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Poetically:[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami[m
[32m+[m[32mSatyananda's                     What kind of thing is Brahman, what is Spirit[m
[32m+[m[32mPreface to the                   What is karma, what is "adhibhut"[m
[32m+[m[32mBengali Edition                  What is called "adhidaiva," O Merciful One[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Sir, bestow me with Your Grace, teach me -1-[m
[32m+[m[32mIntroduction                     Knowing You with still mind at the time of death[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 How can one do that, please tell me -2-[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 1[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 2                        Commentary:[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 3[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 4                        When the previously-mentioned things are experienced by abiding in[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 5                        Kutasthachaitanya, these types of questions arise in the fire element: What is[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 6                        known as Brahman in this all-pervading Infinite Consciousness? What is the[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 7                        spiritual nature of the Ruler of the Universe? Who is the presiding god of the[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 8                        aggregate of the physical elements or, who is the presiding god of the subtle,[m
[32m+[m[32mChapter 9                        supernatural energies? What is the type of sadhana necessary to know all[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 these things, or who is the doer of all those sadhana practices, or the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 bestower of its fruits? How does he reside in this body, and in what way do[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the mind-absorbed, immersed sadhakas leave their bodies while filled with[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the Eternal, Bliss of Knowledge? -1 and 2-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Sri Bhagavan said:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter8.html (1 of 15)4/18/2006 2:42:08 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 10                  aksharam param brahma svabhabohdhyatmamuchyate[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 11                  bhutabhavodbhavakarovisargah karmasamjnitah -3-[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 12                  adhibhutam ksharobhavah purushashchadhidaivatam[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 13                  adhiyajnohhamevatra dehe dehabhritam varah -4-[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 14[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 15                  Poetically:[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 16[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 17                  Hearing this, the Lord spoke[m
[32m+[m[32m     Chapter 18                  Gradually I will tell you Partha, listen attentively[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The Immutable, Param Brahman, who cannot be destroyed[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The sustainer of the Cosmos, all-pervading, revealed Self[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 All bodies are Its part, the same as fire[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 It is known as Spirit[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The different ways God presides in creatures[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 That is known as "adhibhut" -3-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The ruler of all gods in the sun world[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The one who is there is known as "adhidaiva"[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 In all bodies within, fruits come by yajna[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Thus I am the One that is called "adhiyajna" -4-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Commentary:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 The types of realizations that come to be, if one's mind remains focused in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Kutasthachaitanya when these types of questions arise in the energy of fire[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 element, is what is being presented in these slokas. To understand this, it is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 necessary to explain what is "Pranava"; that is being elucidated below.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 OM - this sound is called "Pranava." "A" + "U "+ "M" -- the union of these[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 three sounds comprise this word. "A" means Brahma,* "U" means Vishnu,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "M" means Maheshvara. "A" + "U" = "O" and the "chandrabindu" (a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 phonetic symbol drawn as a crescent with a dot above it - see the OM[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 symbol) takes the place of "M" to represent the nasal sound; as when -[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "bangsha" [bamboo] becomes "ba(n)sh," "hangsa" [swan] becomes "ha(n)s"[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 etc.** [The ‚ÄúOM‚Äù sound is not written in Sanskritic languages with an ‚ÄúM‚Äù,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 but the above-mentioned ‚Äúchandrabindu‚Äù - as it is in the Bengali text in this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Gita as well - and is often pronounced as ‚ÄúONG‚Äù, where the ‚ÄúG‚Äú is never[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 completed.] Thus, the union of Vishnu, Brahma and Maheshvara is the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 meaning of this OM sound. Now, what this aggregate of Brahma, Vishnu[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and Maheshvar is, and what the condition is when they are one -- that needs[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 to somewhat expounded upon.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 [*In the sections marked "Poetically" and "Commentary" in this translation,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Brahma" always means the Creator aspect of the Trinity [Creator, Sustainer,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Destroyer], and "Brahman" always means the Supreme Absolute, which is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 beyond all and is the Source of the Trinity. In many translations, the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 transliteration "Brahma" is used to represent both the Absolute as well as the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Creator aspect, the two being distinguished from each other by phonetic[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 marks representing a short "a" in the end of the word for the Absolute, and a[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter8.html (2 of 15)4/18/2006 2:42:08 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 long "a" at the end of the word for the Creator aspect. Not using phonetic[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 markings in the English parts of this translation, the traditional unmarked[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 transliterations for those two words have been used, as explained above in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 this footnote. The Sanskrit slokas, however, have been transliterated without[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 consideration of such distinctions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 **The "n"s in parentheses are not pronounced as consonants. They indicate a[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 slightly overt nasal sound.][m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 In the first sloka of the first chapter of this book it has been explained that in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 this creation, Consciousness (Spirit) is referred to by these eight names:[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Vishva, Birat, Taijas, Hiranyagarbha, Prajna, Ishvar, Chidabhas and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Kutasthachaitanya. In them, the first six mentioned are presiding in the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 functions of action, and the last two mentioned are existing as two types of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 revelatory aspects. Among the first six states of Consciousness, Vishva and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Birat - meaning the tamas-dominated ones - are existing as the physical form[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of Consciousness, which, because of their nature to transform/destroy, are[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 constantly changing. The one who has been referred to as the Lord of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Destruction/Transformation, or Maheshvar, in the commentary to the eighth[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sloka of the fourth chapter -- that destruction aspect of Consciousness is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 called "adhibhut." Taijas and Hiranyagarbha - meaning the rajas-dominated[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 oness - are the subtle aspects of Consciousness presiding within all physical[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 elements. That which has been called the Lord of Creation, or Brahma -- that[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 is who is the being within the abode of physical creation, and is called the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 creation-causing, demi-god-energy endowed "adhidaiva." And Prajna and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Ishvar - meaning the sattva-dominated - are the aspects of Consciousness[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 presiding in causal form - the one who has been referred Vishnu, the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sustainer/holder of the world. Being self-revealed, he is the one who is called[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "adhyatma."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 By the practice of Sadguru-instructed Kriya and by the study of the matters[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of Self, with mind completely focused, sadhakas gradually come to know[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 their own physical bodies to be the aggregate of the Cosmos, or Birat -[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 meaning the "adhibhut" Mahaeshvar; having done so, they experience the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 form of the subtle body within that [the physical body] - Taijas's sum total[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 form of Hiranyagarbha - meaning Brahma, that "adhidaiva" by whom all[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 physical aspects of creation are appearing; after which, sadhakas experience[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 its [the physical and subtle aspects'] sustainer/holder - the causal body's sum[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 total, known as Ishvar-consciousness. That Ishvar-consciousness is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 manifesting all aspects of both the physical and subtle aspects of creation. In[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 this state, sadhakas experience the aforementioned "Pranava" with complete[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 clarity. For this reason, this [Pranava] is call "Ishvar-vachak" [the Word[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 pertaining to Ishvar]. For the sake of explanation, this is what the saintly[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 scriptural scholars have described as the simultaneously arising OM Pranava[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sound as the united condition of the aforementioned Brahma-, Vishnu- and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Maheshvar-knowing three letters of A, U, M. The highest purpose of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Pranava, because mind comes near to the Lord by its experience, is[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter8.html (3 of 15)4/18/2006 2:42:08 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 "Ishvarpranidhan" [meditating on Ishvar]. By it, the subconscious becomes[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 exposed, all obstacles are destroyed, and mind easily becomes absorbed in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the Divine. For this reason, it is this subconscious-exposing Omkar Sound, or[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Pranava, that they call the Religion of the Self ["atmadharma"]. This state is[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the highest. If one can abide in this state, then nothing remains unknown in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 creation - physical, subtle, etc., and even when Brahma and all the others are[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 destroyed in the time of dissolution, this state never ends. As in Patanjal -[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 ishvara pranidhanadva -- no. 23[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tasya vachakah pranavah -- no. 23[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tajjapastadarthabhavanam -- no. 28[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tatah pratyakchetanadhigamohpantarayabhavashcha -- no. 29[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tatraniratishayam sarvajnabijam -- no. 25[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sa esha purveshamapi guruh kalenanavacchedat -- no. 26 ity samadhipadah[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Thus, this creation is existing due to the conglomeration of adhibhut,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 adhidaiva and adhyatma, and only by the Atman-Kriya Pranava is the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Essence of Consciousness manifest in the elements. But none of the above-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 mentioned in creation is self-manifesting; therefore, even Pranava is not self-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 revealing, and neither is the Essence of Consciousness manifesting in all[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 elements by it. Chidabhas and Kutasthachaitanya are present in creation to[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 reveal all of them; this has already been previously explained. In that, the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Abhaschaitanya [Chidabhas] is only the reflection of Kutasthachaitanya; this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 has been explained in the first sloka of the first chapter. Therefore, only[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Kutasthachaitanya is the revealer of all creation, and thereby also the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 revealer of the Atman-Kriya Pranava. By the Sadguru-graced techniques,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 taking recourse in Kutasthachaitanya Itself, gradually becoming purified, and[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 realizing Pranava, sadhakas experience the entire adhibhautik [physical[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 essence], adhidaivik [subtle essence] and adhyatmik [causal essence][m
[32m+[m[32m                                 comprised creation. It is this Kutasthachaitanya that is every yajna, meaning[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the Lord of the Consciousness-revealing Kriya; it is by taking recourse in[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 This and by This, being engaged in Kriya, that sadhakas experience the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 whole of creation as revealed within themselves. It this Kutasthachaitanya[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 that is present as the Supreme in all creation, and therefore also in the bodies[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 of the embodied.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 That Boundless, Infinite Consciousness Who is Above All, and is gracefully[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 abiding as Immutable and Eternal -- That is what is known as Brahman. -3[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and 4-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 antakale cha mameva smaranmuktva kalevaram[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 yah prayati sa madbhavam yati nastyatre samshayah -5-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 yam yam vapi smaran bhavam tyajatyante kalevaram[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tam tamevaiti kaunteya sada tadbhavabhavitah -6-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Poetically:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mfile:///C|/Yoga%20Niketan/sriyukteshvargita/chapter8.html (4 of 15)4/18/2006 2:42:08 PM[m
[32m+[m[32mSwami Sriyukteswar Giri Maharaj        www.yoganiketan.net[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 One who remembers Me at the time of death[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Leaves the body and attains that sacred thing[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 If there is desire of devotion he receives Nirvana, liberation[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 If he is a devotee, of course he comes to My abode -5-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Whatever feelings occur in mind at the time of death[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 That is what one attains, not any other -6-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Commentary:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Because of the united power (resultant force) of the sum total of the[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fluctuations of consciousness at the time of leaving this present physical[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 body, whatever feelings arise in the consciousness of the jiva that are felt at[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 that time, previously powerless, become powerful because of the adjoining[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 lack and need of fulfillment, and therefore that jiva thinks of his state of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 being as that [particular] condition; thus, the jiva assumes another body also[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 based upon that discernment. This subject has been explained in the 70th[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 sloka of the second chapter. For this reason, one who, having stopped all[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 fluctuations of mind, abides in Atman Consciousness -- he, even though he[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 discards the unreliable body, because there are no causes of permutation of[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 creation left, attains with certainty that all-pervading Infinite Consciousness-[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Beingness. There is not a bit of doubt about that. -5 and 6-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 tasmat sarveshu kaleshu mamanusmara yudhya cha[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 majyarpitamanobuddhirmamevaishyasyasamshayam -7-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Poetically:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Therefore, constantly remember Me[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Fight on, know that there is no death in this[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Surrendering mind and intellect in Me[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 You will get Me; nothing wrong will happen -7-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Commentary:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 Therefore, one should always be attentive to Kutasthachaitanya and practice[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 the Religion of Self - practice the Sadguru-given Kriya; by this, the doubting[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 mind and the endeavoring intellect become merged in Atman-Consciousness,[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 and one can reside in Atman-Consciousness with certainty. -7-[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m                                 abhyasayogamuktena chetasa nanyagamina[m
